    <h1>Cat Care Guide</h1>

    <p><strong>1. Nutrition:</strong> Provide a well-balanced and age-appropriate diet. Consult your veterinarian for dietary recommendations and feeding schedules.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Hydration:</strong> Ensure a fresh and clean water supply at all times. Cats may not drink as much as dogs, so encourage water intake through wet food or cat fountains.</p>

    <p><strong>3. Grooming:</strong> Brush your cat's fur regularly to reduce shedding and prevent matting. Long-haired breeds may require more frequent grooming.</p>

    <p><strong>4. Veterinary Care:</strong> Schedule regular veterinary check-ups. Keep vaccinations, parasite prevention, and dental care up-to-date for your cat's overall health.</p>

    <p><strong>5. Litter Box Maintenance:</strong> Keep the litter box clean by scooping it daily. Provide a quiet and accessible location for your cat to use the litter box.</p>

    <p><strong>6. Enrichment:</strong> Cats need mental and physical stimulation. Provide toys, scratching posts, and opportunities for climbing to keep your cat entertained.</p>

    <p><strong>7. Safe Environment:</strong> Create a safe indoor environment. Ensure windows and balconies are secure, and toxic plants or substances are out of reach.</p>

    <p><strong>8. Identification:</strong> Keep a collar with an ID tag on your cat, and consider microchipping for added security in case your cat gets lost.</p>

    <p><strong>9. Social Interaction:</strong> Spend quality time with your cat. Cats enjoy gentle play, and some may appreciate lap time or being held. Respect your cat's preferences.</p>

    <p><strong>10. Spaying/Neutering:</strong> Consider spaying or neutering your cat unless you plan to breed. This helps prevent unwanted behaviors and contributes to population control.</p>
    
